Automated Test Equipment

12/13/2025
Michelle Yang (my394), Diane Pillsbury (dmp282), Xia Yan Zhao (xz834)

Automated IC tester with Raspberry Pi Pico Demonstration Video

Introduction

Sound Bite: The ATE74IC can automatically test a variety of 74-series integrated circuits with the press of a button, preventing users from wasting time with faulty circuits.

Summary: The ATE74IC is a testing device that tests the validity of each gate within each IC chip. This project tested specifically 6 IC chips: NAND, NOT, OR, AND, D Flip Flop, and NOR. These are common chips used to design complex ASIC designs and processors. Ensuring these chips work is crucial in developing digital electronics as they are vital to developing everyday systems that people use.

Rationale and Sources:

Automated test equipment is used extensively in the semiconductor industry to quickly test chips for manufacturing flaws; as integrated circuits and systems-on-chip grow increasingly complex, testing each internal connection becomes difficult, so equipment to automatically run tests becomes necessary. However, aspects of semiconductor testing, including Design for Test, post-silicon validation, and automated test equipment, are rarely mentioned in undergraduate-level courses. Additionally, having equipment to test ICs commonly used in digital electronics courses would be greatly beneficial, as would save time working with faulty chips. We designed the ATE74IC to provide an accessible interface for undergraduates to test simple 74-series ICs.

Background:

A selection of 7400-series integrated circuits were chosen as the units-under-test (UUTs) for this project since the 7400-series is an industry standard commonly used in many digital electronics courses. These logic ICs implement fundamental Boolean functions (AND, OR, NAND, NOT) and sequential elements like (D flip flops) in a 14 pin package. The pinout conventions and well documented specifications make them really suited for this project.

ATE systems verify electronic component functionality through a computer controlling testing scheme without manual intervention. Our implementation focuses on functional testing by applying systematic input patterns to the IC and comparing the measured outputs against expected values derived from truth tables. For combinational logic gates, we use exhaustive truth table verification that tests all possible input combinations. For sequential circuits like D flip-flops, we employ clock cycle based validation that verifies state transitions over multiple clock edges.

The user interface leverages VGA display to provide clear visual feedback. Using Hunter Adam’s VGA library for the RP2040’s dual core architecture allows one core to handle the timing of the VGA signals while the other manages test execution and user interactions. The display shows IC package representations with color coded pins to show pass/fail.

To enhance useability, we incorporated audio feedback using pre-recorded speech samples played through an SPI connected DAC. When the system detects either pass or fail, it plays corresponding audio messages that alert users to the failure type. This auditory confirmation allows users to identify problems immediately without needing to constantly watch the display.

High Level Design

Logical Structure:

We found it most intuitive to divide the code into multiple files for this project due to the scope and necessity of asynchronous work. We put the “main” function, all code for protothreads, button, VGA, LED, and DAC in a file entitled “ate.c”. However, all test functions were placed in a file titled “atpg.c”, (Automated Test Pattern Generator). Variables needed in ate.c and atpg.c are in a “ate_variables.c”, which is included in atpg.c. Additionally, due to the length of bitmap arrays, they were placed in a separate file entitled “bitmap.c.” Similarly, the arrays encoding the audio samples were placed in separate header files (“audio_pass.h” and “audio_fail.h”).

Additionally, we used semaphores to control when VGA and test protothreads ran; for example, calling the VGA semaphore after the button to toggle between ICs is pressed.

Hardware/Software Tradeoffs

Since 7400-series ICs have 12 pins (not counting ground and VCC pins), we realized the number of GPIOs we had on a standard RP2040 would be inadequate if we wanted to also use buttons, LEDs, and a DAC. We decided that these were all important elements of the project which we did not wish to sacrifice, so we obtained a port expander (the MCP23s17). The port expander allows us to provide more digital I/O to the RP2040 at the expense of a slower clock rate. Since the test functions are relatively simple, the slower clock cycle was imperceptible to results speed.

Additionally, many design decisions, such as the extensive use of functions and text variables, were the result of prioritizing simplicity and readability by humans over space or time constraints. Since the project was not especially space or time-intensive, we did not worry about those as constraints, and instead aimed to make the code and display intuitive for us to create in our four-week timespan as well as for the target demographic of undergraduate students.


Program/hardware Design

Hardware:

The ATE74IC hardware centers around the RP2040 microcontroller, which handles test operations, manages the user interface, and generates VGA display output. To solve our GPIO pin limitations when interfacing with 14-pin ICs while supporting buttons, LEDs, and display generation, we decided to use an MCP23S17 SPI port expander to provide 16 additional bidirectional I/O pins. This was suggested by Bruce Land and it allowed dynamic configuration of each IC pin as input or output during testing. The user interface features two push buttons (IC selection and test start) and red/green status LEDs for immediate visual feedback. The VGA subsystem uses a resistor based DAC network to generate color signals, displaying the IC under test with color coded pins. Audio feedback is delivered through an SPI DAC and 3.5mm audio jack, playing pre-recorded messages for test results.

The hardware we used for the project was as follows:

  • RP2040
  • Port expander (MCP23s17)
  • LEDs (One red and one green)
  • Buttons (two)
  • Two 330 Ohm resistors
  • VGA
  • VGA adapter
  • DAC
  • Audio Jack
  • Wires
  • 7400-series ICs (7400, 7402, 7404, 7408, 7432, 7474)

Software:

As discussed above, we divided software into protothreads and files to divide functionality.

  • ATPG:
    “ATPG” stands for Automatic Test Pattern Generator, and in industry, this is a part of an ATE or on-chip Built-In-Self-Test system which generates test cases to try to achieve full coverage of all connections on the chip. However, for the scope of this project we hard-coded test cases, which was a far simpler way to achieve coverage since the number of possible values is very low for 74-series ICs. The “atpg.c” file includes functions to test each 74-series UUT. While the test cases themselves were relatively simple; we ran into several challenges in this section of the project. The most immediately obvious problem was that the RP2040 has only twenty-five GPIO pins available, and we needed twenty-six to incorporate all of our desired functionality, as discussed in the Hardware-software tradeoffs section. As a result, we had to use a MCP23s17 port expander and an associated library provided by Bruce Land in the ATPG test functions. We set up port expander directions, and reset output LEDs and stored results at the top of each function, then proceeded to cycle through each test case. For each test case, we set the port expander outputs / UUT inputs to selected test values, then stored the UUT outputs in an array, which we checked for accuracy to expected values. These results were then output to the VGA, followed by the start of the next test case. This was our next challenge; transferring results to the display; this was solved by writing to a thoughtfully designed system of structs and arrays in the “ate_variables.c” file. Finally, testing the D-Flip-Flop IC (7474) was slightly challenging since it required multiple cycles of the clock pin to test. To simulate this, we cycled the clock in increments of five microseconds using a sleep function.
  • Buttons:
    The button control was confined to the thread “protothread_button”, and relied on a debouncing state machine for each button. On the transition from the “Maybe Pressed” to “Pressed” state for the “Gate Select” button, the ic_name variable for the current test is updated to the the next gate, where each gate is represented by an integer between zero and six, and the integer is incremented on the state transition. Similarly, the “Start Test” button calls the test_semaphore to run the test protothread on the transition from MAYBE_NOT_PRESSED to NOT_PRESSED. Choosing to place the test functionality in a separate protothread called by a semaphore allows control over when tests are run. This way, the operator can ensure the setup is correct before running, view test results in real time, keep test results up as long as desired, and rerun when ready.
  • VGA Screen Top-Left IC chip Test Bed & Bitmap:
    The top left section of the VGA screen displays a visual representation of the IC chip test bed, showing the chip outline with pin numbers and connections that highlight in red when a pin fails a test. Black and white line-art images of 7400-series IC chips (7404 NOT, 7408 AND, 7400 NAND, 7432 OR, 7402 NOR, 7474 DFF) were sourced from Google and converted to bitmap arrays using an online image-to-bitmap converter tool, image2cpp. However, many of the Google images were too blurry, resulting in bitmap representations where the gate symbols were hard to read, pin labels didn't align properly with the test bed connections, and some gate triangles had missing lines. To fix these issues, we manually edited the bitmap arrays in bitmap.c, modifying the 0x00FFFFFF (white) and 0x00000000 (black) hex values pixel by pixel to clean up the gate symbols, straighten lines, and ensure the chip diagrams were legible and properly aligned. The draw_ic_chip() function renders these bitmaps by iterating through each pixel and calling drawPixel(), while draw_pin_connection() draws the pin labels and connection lines, changing the color to red and using fillRect() instead of drawLine() for any pins marked as failed in the current_test struct. Highlighting “0x00FFFFFF” then command+f (find), makes it easier to visualize which 0x00FFFFFFs and 0x00000000 should be added or deleted.
  • VGA Screen Top-Right Real-Time Test Progress
    The top right section of the VGA screen displays real-time test progress through the draw_error_messages_display function, which shows the current test number (for example, “Test 2 of 4”), the current status message indicating which gate is being tested (for example, “Runnng test 2 on gate 1…”), and a list of gate results that updates as each gate completes testing. The TestProgress struct in ate_variables.c tracks these informations with fields for current_test_num, total_tests, current_gate_num, total_gates, current_status, gate_results[], and a test_in_progress flag. During testing, atpg.c updates these fields and calls update_vga_display() to reflect these changes. If the gate failed a test, the result in displayed in red. The test_in_progress flag turns false, and the final frame shows all gates complete testing, and a list of gate test results.
  • Audio:
    To achieve audio output, we connected a MCP4822 12-bit DAC to the RP2040 via SPI communication. The DAC output connects to an audio jack, which connects to the speaker. We generated two audio clips, “All tests pass; the IC chip works correctly” or “Some tests failed; the IC chip might be faulty” using a text to speech website, TTSMP3. Next, we converted the MP3 file to an uncompressed, WAV file ((uncompressed, sample rate 8000 Hz, 8-bit unsigned, mono channel) using another online converter, FreeConvert. Finally, we converted the WAV file to C array header (code format hex 0x00, data type uint8_t, unsigned) using FileToCArray. We initialized the SPI ports in ate.c, and played the two audio samples by looping through the two arrays, scaling each of the 9-bit sample to 12-bit for our 12-bit DAC, and sending it via SPI. Audio error messages are played after each test completes, based on the test results.

The “atpg.c” file includes functions to test each UUT.

AI Use

We used AI (ChatGPT) to generate some code, but all code was heavily modified from the ChatGPT output. The main use case was getting an example of how to do something in C which we didn’t already know how to do.

Results of the Design

Our testing revealed that the ATE worked for all test ICs.

The top left of the VGA screen highlights failed pins in red. The top right of the VGA screen displays test results in real time while the test is running. The green “Overall Pass” LED lights up only when all test cases for all gates pass, while the red “Overall Fail” LED lights up when one or more test cases fail. The bottom section of the VGA screen displays a results summary, indicating which output pin produces an incorrect value. An audio version of the results summary also plays. We added audio output to enhance accessibility for users who may have difficulty seeing the display. In a future version of this project, we plan to expand the audio feedback to provide more detailed messages, rather than only the two current messages: “All tests pass; the IC chip works correctly” or “Some tests failed; the IC chip might be faulty.”

The top right section of the VGA screen shows, in real time, which gate on the IC is currently being tested, as well as which test case is running. A sleep_ms delay was added to the program to slow down the testing process, allowing this portion of the VGA display to update visibly. Without sleep_ms, the test completes in less than one second, causing the top right section of the VGA screen to display only its final frame, the summary of the specific tests that failed.

We tested two units of each 7400-series IC chip. As demonstrated in the demo video above, one of the 7400 NAND chips sourced from DigiKey was defective. As expected, our automatic test equipment correctly identified this damaged chip and reported a failed result.

We also intentionally shortened some of the input or output pins of the ICs to ground, VCC, or to each other to induce failures. In these cases, the top right section of the VGA screen correctly indicated a failure at the output associated with the shorted pin, along with the specific failed test case (for example, “110 fault gate 1”, indicating that when two logic-high inputs were applied to a NAND gate, the expected logic-low output was not observed and a logic-high output was produced instead).

7400-series IC Type Test Results
7400 (NAND) One chip pass, one chip fail
7402 (NOR) Both chips pass: Green light works. Displays expected error messages.
7404 (NOT) Both chips pass: Green light works. Displays expected error messages.
7408 (AND) Both chips pass: Green light works. Displays expected error messages.
7432 (OR) Both chips pass: Green light works. Displays expected error messages.
7474 (DFF) Both chips pass: Green light works. Displays expected error messages.

Conclusions

Our ATE74IC successfully met its primary objective of automatically testing the 74-series logic ICs with a single debouncing button that switches between the different gates. The system accurately identifies and tests common logic gates (AND, OR, NOT, NAD, NOR, XOR, D Flip Flops) and displays results on a VGA monitor and circuit board LED with clear pass fail indicators. The RP2040 did not have enough GPIO pins so we used a port extender and it worked well. The truth table verification proved to be reliable for combinational logic testing. The user interface provided very clear feedback and is very intuitive for the users to understand. This application is good for educational or hobbyist applications.

Next time, we believe we can have a more expanded IC library since we are only limited to basic gates and flip-flops. We can also include counters, registers, and more complex 74 series devices. Also, having a data logging system that allows exportation of test results via USB serial would be helpful for sharing among teams.

For code, we utilized Hunter Adam’s VGA graphics library for the RP2040, which is publicly available and documented for educational use in ECE 4760 class. The standard pico sdk libraries were used for GPIO control, spi communication, and hardware timers. Additionally, we used the MCP23S17 port expander library (mcp23s17_rp2040.h) provided by Bruce Land for spi-based GPIO expansion functionality. The test generation logic (atpg.c), user interface, the IC tests and state controls were our own original work. The IC chip visual representation displayed on the VGA interface use bitmap images so it would look neater on the VGA. These graphics are our original artwork based on standard IC package appearance and are not from any copyrighted material.

In terms of public domain usage, 74-series IC specifications are based on decades old designs now in the public domain. Logic function definitions are Boolean operations not subject to intellectual property protection. Truth tables and timing requirements were derived from publicly available datasheets from manufacturers (Texas Instruments, NXP, ON Semiconductor). We did not reverse engineer any commercial ATE system. Our test methodology is comparing actual IC outputs against expected truth tables. No proprietary testing algorithm or commercial test equipment designs were replicated.

Patents and trademarks: the 74 series is not trademarked because it is industry standard. Commercial ATE patents exist but are much better than our educational implementation. All components are standard commercial parts with no NDAs. This project presents no patent opportunities as IC testing is well-established technology

/**
 * ate.c (hardcode for NOT gate first?)
 * 
 * 
 * HARDWARE CONNECTIONS
 *  - GPIO 16 ---> VGA Hsync
 *  - GPIO 17 ---> VGA Vsync
 *  - GPIO 18 ---> 470 ohm resistor ---> VGA Green
 *  - GPIO 19 ---> 330 ohm resistor ---> VGA Green
 *  - GPIO 20 ---> 330 ohm resistor ---> VGA Blue
 *  - GPIO 21 ---> 330 ohm resistor ---> VGA Red
 *  - RP2040 GND ---> VGA GND
 * 
 * RP2040 to DAC  
 * - GPIO 5 --> Chip select
 * - GPIO 6 --> SCK/spi0_sclk
 * - GPIO 7 --> MOSI/spix0_tx
 * - GPIO 2 --> GPIO output for timing ISR
 * - RP2040 --> GND LDAC
 * - RP2040 3.3v -> VCC on DAC 
 * - RP2040 GND -> GND on DAC 
 * 
 * RP2040 to LED 
 * - GPIO 25 ---> on-board LED 
 * - GPIO 8 ---> green LED (test pass)
 * - GPIO 9 ---> red LED (test fail)
 * 
 * RP2040 to physical buttons
 * - GPIO 14 ---> toggle IC button (cycles through NAND, NOR, NOT, AND, OR, and D FLIP-FLOP)
 * - GPIO 15 ---> start test button
 * 
 * RP2040 to port expansion 
 * - GPIO 10 ---> SCK (pin 12)
 * - GPIO 11 ---> TX (pin 13)
 * - GPIO 12 ---> RX (pin 14)
 * - GPIO 13 ---> CS (pin 11)
 * - RP2040 3.3v -> Vdd (pin 9), reset (pin 18)
 * - RP2040 GND -> Vss (pin 10), AIN0, AIN1, AIN2 address (pins 15, 16, 17)
 * 
 * Port expansion to IC test bed
 * Port B (GPB 0 to GPB 6) ---> left test bed
 * GPB 0 ---> pin 1
 * GPB 1 ---> pin 2
 * GPB 2 ---> pin 3
 * GPB 3 ---> pin 4
 * GPB 4 ---> pin 5
 * GPB 5 ---> pin 6
 * GPB 6 ---> pin 7
 * Port A (GPA 0 to GPA 6) ---> right test bed
 * GPA 0 ---> pin 8
 * GPA 1 ---> pin 9
 * GPA 2 ---> pin 10
 * GPA 3 ---> pin 11
 * GPA 4 ---> pin 12
 * GPA 5 ---> pin 13
 * GPA 6 ---> pin 14
 * 
 */

// IC package
void draw_ic_chip(int x, int y) {
    int ic_width  = 80;
    int ic_height = 120;

    // Draw background and border
    fillRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, BLACK);
    drawRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, WHITE);

    // Draw bitmap inside the chip area
    switch(currentGate){
      case GATE_NONE:
        fillRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, BLACK);
        drawRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, WHITE);
        break;
      case GATE_NOT:
        for (int row = 0; row < ic_height; row++) {
            for (int col = 0; col < ic_width; col++) {
                uint16_t pixel = ic7404_bitmap[row * ic_width + col];

                drawPixel(x + col, y + row, pixel);
            }
        }
        drawRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, WHITE);
        break;
      case GATE_AND:
        for (int row = 0; row < ic_height; row++) {
            for (int col = 0; col < ic_width; col++) {
                uint16_t pixel = ic7408_bitmap[row * ic_width + col];

                drawPixel(x + col, y + row, pixel);
            }
        }
        drawRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, WHITE);
        break;
      case GATE_NAND:
        for (int row = 0; row < ic_height; row++) {
            for (int col = 0; col < ic_width; col++) {
                uint16_t pixel = ic7400_bitmap[row * ic_width + col];

                drawPixel(x + col, y + row, pixel);
            }
        }
        drawRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, WHITE);
        break;
      case GATE_OR:
        for (int row = 0; row < ic_height; row++) {
            for (int col = 0; col < ic_width; col++) {
                uint16_t pixel = ic7432_bitmap[row * ic_width + col];

                drawPixel(x + col, y + row, pixel);
            }
        }
        drawRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, WHITE);
        break;
      case GATE_NOR:
        for (int row = 0; row < ic_height; row++) {
            for (int col = 0; col < ic_width; col++) {
                uint16_t pixel = ic7402_bitmap[row * ic_width + col];

                drawPixel(x + col, y + row, pixel);
            }
        }
        drawRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, WHITE);
        break;
      case GATE_DFF:
        for (int row = 0; row < ic_height; row++) {
            for (int col = 0; col < ic_width; col++) {
                uint16_t pixel = ic7474_bitmap[row * ic_width + col];

                drawPixel(x + col, y + row, pixel);
            }
        }
        drawRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, WHITE);
        break;
    }
}


// Draw pin with connection line
void draw_pin_connection(int pin_num, int x, int y, bool is_left, bool failed) {
  //Write pin number  
  char pin_str[4];
    if(pin_num == 14){
      sprintf(pin_str, "Vdd");
    }else if(pin_num == 7){
      sprintf(pin_str, "GND");
    }else{
      sprintf(pin_str, "%d", pin_num);
    }

    if (failed) {
        setTextColor(RED);
        // int x_mark = is_left ? (x + 40) : (x - 40);

        // Red connection line for failed pin
        fillRect(is_left ? x : (x - 10), y - 1, 10, 3, RED);
        
        // Red pin number
        setCursor(is_left ? (x - 15) : (x + 10), y - 4);
        writeString(pin_str);
        
    } else {
        setTextColor(WHITE);
        
        drawLine(is_left ? x : (x - 10), y, is_left ? (x + 10) : x, y, WHITE);
        
        setCursor(is_left ? (x - 15) : (x + 10), y - 4);
        writeString(pin_str);
    }
}

// Main IC test display function
void draw_ic_test_display(int x, int y) {
    fillRect(x, y, 300, 250, BLACK);
    drawRect(x, y, 300, 250, WHITE);
    
    setTextColor(WHITE);
    setTextSize(1);
    setCursor(x + 10, y + 10);
    writeString(current_test.ic_name);
    
    // FAIL/PASS status
    setTextSize(1);
    if (current_test.overall_pass == 1)  {
      setTextColor(WHITE);
      setCursor(x + 130, y + 30);
      writeString("PASS");
    } else if(current_test.overall_pass == 0) {
      setTextColor(WHITE);  
      setCursor(x + 130, y + 30);
      writeString("FAIL");
    }else {
      setTextColor(WHITE);  
      setCursor(x + 130, y + 30);
      writeString("NOT TESTED");
    }
    
    // Breadboard background
    int board_x = x + 50;
    int board_y = y + 60;
    int board_width = 200;
    int board_height = 130;
    
    // IC chip in center
    int ic_x = board_x + 60;
    int ic_y = board_y + 15;
    draw_ic_chip(ic_x, ic_y);
    
    // Draw pins 7 on each side 
    int pin_spacing = 15;
    int pin_start_y = ic_y + 13;
    
    // Left side pins (1-7)
    for (int i = 0; i < 7; i++) {
        int pin_y = pin_start_y + i * pin_spacing;
        bool failed = current_test.pins[i].failed ;
        printf("%d",failed) ; // serial UART terminal
        draw_pin_connection(i + 1, ic_x - 10, pin_y, true, failed);
    }
    
    // Right side pins (14-8, top to bottom)
    for (int i = 0; i < 7; i++) {
        int pin_num = 14 - i;
        int pin_y = pin_start_y + i * pin_spacing;
        bool failed = current_test.pins[13-i].failed ;
        draw_pin_connection(pin_num, ic_x + 90, pin_y, false, failed);
    }
}

// Display error messages (top right side)
void draw_error_messages_display(int x, int y) {
    fillRect(x, y, 300, 250, BLACK);
    
    setTextColor(WHITE);
    setTextSize(1);
    setCursor(x + 10, y + 10);
    writeString("Testing ...");
    drawHLine(x + 10, y + 20, 100, WHITE); // underline
    
    if (test_progress.test_in_progress) {
      char msg[50];
      snprintf(msg, sizeof(msg), "Test %d of %d", test_progress.current_test_num, test_progress.total_tests);
      setCursor(x + 10, y + 35);
      writeString(msg);

      // current status
      setCursor(x + 10, y + 55);
      writeString(test_progress.current_status);

      // gate results
      setCursor(x + 10, y + 80);
      writeString("Gate Results:");
      for (int i = 0; i < test_progress.total_gates && i < 6; i++) {
        setCursor(x + 10, y + 95 + (i * 14));
        if (test_progress.gate_results[i][0] != '\0') { // don't display empty gate array slot
          setTextColor(WHITE);
        } else {
          setTextColor(RED);
        }
        writeString(test_progress.gate_results[i]);
        setTextColor(WHITE);
      }
      
    } else {
      setCursor(x + 10, y + 35);
      if (current_test.overall_pass == 2) {
        writeString("Press GATE button to toggle between gates."); // initial msg
        setCursor(x + 10, y + 55);
        writeString("Press START button to begin test.");
      } else if (current_test.overall_pass == 1) {
        setTextColor(WHITE);
        writeString("All tests PASSED!");
      } else {
        setTextColor(RED);
        writeString("Tests FAILED!");
        setTextColor(WHITE);
        // show failed tests
        char fail_list[500];
        strncpy(fail_list, failed_tests, sizeof(fail_list));
        char *line = strtok(fail_list, "\n");
        int line_y = y + 55;
        while(line && line_y < y + 240) {
          setCursor(x + 10, line_y);
          setTextColor(RED);
          writeString(line);
          setTextColor(WHITE);
          line_y += 14;
          line = strtok(NULL, "\n");

        }
      }
    }
    // // case statement, shows result of running different tests?
    // switch(current_test.overall_pass){
    //     case(2): // NOT TESTED
    //         writeString("Test incomplete");
    //         break;
    //     case(1): // PASS
    //         writeString("All Test Cases Passed");
    //         break;
    //     case(0): // Fail
    //         writeString(failed_tests);
    //         break;
    
    // }
   
}

// Display error summary
void draw_error_summary_display(int x, int y) {
    fillRect(x, y, 600, 250, BLACK);
    
    setTextColor(WHITE);
    setTextSize(1);
    setCursor(x, y + 10);
    writeString("IC Chip Test Result Summary");
    drawHLine(x, y + 20, 175, WHITE); // underline

    if (current_test.overall_pass != 2) { // start button pressed
      // name of ic chip
      setCursor(x, y + 35);
      writeString("IC Chip: ");
      writeString(current_test.ic_name);
    
      bool all_passed = false;
      for (int i = 0; i < 14; i++) {
        // Skipped VCC & GND
        if (i == 6 || i == 13) continue; 
        if (current_test.pins[i].failed) {
          all_passed = false;
          break;
        }
      }

      // if all pass, don't show IC Chip: (nothing)
      if (all_passed == false) {
        // Display failed pins 
        setCursor(x, y + 55);
        writeString("Wrong output: ");

        setTextColor(RED);
        for (int i = 0; i < 14; i++) {
          // Skipped VCC & GND
          if (i == 6 || i == 13) continue; 
          if (current_test.pins[i].failed) {
            sprintf(screentext, "%d", current_test.pins[i].pin_num);
            writeString(screentext);
            writeString("  ");

          }
        }
      }
      
      // Summary text?
      setTextColor(WHITE);
      setCursor(x, y + 80);
      if (current_test.overall_pass == 0) {
        writeString("Some tests failed; the IC chip might be faulty.");
        // writeString("This  IC Chip might actually be a ...");  // Display guessed IC Chip 
      } else {
        writeString("All tests pass; the IC Chip works correctly.");
      }
    }
    
}

// Called by atpg.c to update VGA screen
void update_vga_display(void) {
  draw_ic_test_display(ic_x, ic_y);
  draw_error_messages_display(error_msg_x, error_msg_y);
  draw_error_summary_display(error_summary_x, error_summary_y);

}

// Audio!!! 
// Second 12 bit value to the DAC
static inline void dac_write(uint16_t value) {
    DAC_data_0 = DAC_config_chan_A | (value & 0x0FFF);
    spi_write16_blocking(AUDIO_SPI_PORT, &DAC_data_0, 1);
}

void clear_gate_results(void) {
    for (int i = 0; i < 6; i ++) {
        test_progress.gate_results[i][0] = '\0'; // null character
    }

ICTestDisplay test_NOT(ICTestDisplay  test) {
    PEinit() ;
    bool correct = 1;
    failed_tests[0] = '\0';


    test_progress.test_in_progress = true; // vga display test result while test is in progress
    test_progress.total_tests = 2;
    test_progress.total_gates = 6;
    clear_gate_results(); // reset

    //reset status LEDs
    gpio_put(LED_RED, 0);
    gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 0);

    //set ports for inverter
    // 1 --> output
    // 0 --> input
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTA,0xea) ; // 1110 1010 --> 0xea
    
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTB, 0xd5) ; // 1101 0101 --> 0xd5

    //results 
    bool actual_output[6];

    // Test 1 
    test_progress.current_test_num = 1;
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "Test 1: Setting inputs HIGH...", 50);
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(500); // allow VGA screen to display ^ --> if no sleep, the entire test finishes too fast to display anthing

    // Set input --> 1
    // Expected output --> 0
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 1) ;
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 1) ;
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 1) ;
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 0, 1) ;
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 2, 1) ;
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 1) ;

    //read output 
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 4) ; //pin 12
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 2) ; //pin 10
    actual_output[2] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 0) ; //pin 8
    actual_output[3] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 5) ; //pin 6
    actual_output[4] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 3) ; //pin 4
    actual_output[5] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 1) ; //pin 2

    //testing...each gate
    for (int gate_num = 0; gate_num < 6; gate_num+=1) {
        // update progress
        test_progress.current_gate_num = gate_num;
        snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Test 1: Checking gate %d...", gate_num + 1); // write string to character array
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(1000); // vga display ^

        if(actual_output[gate_num] != 0) {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: High to Low transition fault", gate_num + 1);
            char testFail[50];  // temporary buffer
            snprintf(testFail, sizeof(testFail), "High to Low transition fault gate %d\n", gate_num + 1) ;
            strncat(failed_tests, testFail, sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1) ;
            //printf("High to Low transition fault for NOT gate %d", gate_num);
            gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
            correct = 0;
            test.overall_pass = 0;
            test.pins[12-2*gate_num-1].failed = true;
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        }
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500); // vga display ^
    }


    // Test 2
    test_progress.current_test_num = 2;
    clear_gate_results();
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "Test 2: Setting inputs LOW...", 50);
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(1000); 

    // Set input --> 0
    // Expected output --> 1
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 0) ;
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 0) ;
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 0) ;
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 0, 0) ;
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 2, 0) ;
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 0) ;

    //read output
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 4) ;
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 2) ;
    actual_output[2] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 0) ;
    actual_output[3] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 5) ;
    actual_output[4] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 3) ;
    actual_output[5] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 1) ;

    //testing...
    for (int gate_num = 0; gate_num < 6; gate_num+=1) {
        test_progress.current_gate_num = gate_num;
        snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Test 2: Checking gate %d...", gate_num + 1); 
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);

        if(actual_output[gate_num] != 1) {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: Low to High transition fault", gate_num + 1);
            char testFail[50];
            snprintf(testFail, sizeof(testFail), "Low to High transition fault gate %d", gate_num + 1) ;
            strncat(failed_tests, testFail, sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1) ;
            gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
            correct = 0;
            test.overall_pass = 0;
            test.pins[12-2*gate_num-1].failed = true;
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        }
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
    }

    // quickly check other gates (wrong gate might be tested)?
    
    if(correct == 1){
        gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 1);
        test.overall_pass = 1;
    }

    test_progress.test_in_progress = false;
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "All tests complete!", 50);
    update_vga_display(); // until switch test

    return test;
    	
}

ICTestDisplay test_AND(ICTestDisplay  test) {
    PEinit() ;
    bool correct = 1;
    failed_tests[0] = '\0';

    test_progress.test_in_progress = true;
    test_progress.total_tests = 4;
    test_progress.total_gates = 4;
    clear_gate_results();

    //reset status LEDs
    gpio_put(LED_RED, 0);
    gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 0);

    //set ports for inverter
    // 1 --> output
    // 0 --> input
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTA, 0xf6) ; // 1111 0110 --> 0xf6 15 6
    
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTB, 0xdb) ; // 1101 1011 --> 0xdb 13 11

    //results 
    bool actual_output[4];

    // Test 1 
    test_progress.current_test_num = 1;
    clear_gate_results();
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "Test 1: Input 00...", 50);
    sleep_ms(1000);

    // Set input --> 00
    // Expected output --> 0
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 0, 0) ; //output B2 (pin 3)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 1, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 3, 0) ; //output B5 (pin 6)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 0) ; //output A0 (pin 8)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 2, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 0) ; //output A3 (pin 11)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 0) ;


    //read output 
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 2) ; //pin 3
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 5) ; //pin 6
    actual_output[2] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 0) ; //pin 8
    actual_output[3] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 3) ; //pin 11


    //testing...
    for (int gate_num = 0; gate_num < 4; gate_num+=1) {
        test_progress.current_gate_num = gate_num;
        snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Test 1: Checking gate %d...", gate_num + 1);
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);

        if(actual_output[gate_num] != 0) {
            char testFail[80];
            snprintf(testFail, sizeof(testFail), "000 fault gate %d\n", gate_num + 1);
            strncat(failed_tests, testFail, sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: 000 fault", gate_num + 1);
            gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
            correct = 0;
            test.overall_pass = 0;
            switch(gate_num){
                case 0: 
                    test.pins[2].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 1:
                    test.pins[5].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 2:
                    test.pins[7].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 3:
                    test.pins[10].failed = true;
                    break;
            }
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        }
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
    }

    // Test 2
    test_progress.current_test_num = 2;
    clear_gate_results();
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "Test 2: Input 01...", 50);
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(1000);

    // Set input --> 01
    // Expected output --> 0
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 0, 0) ; //output B2 (pin 3)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 1, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 3, 0) ; //output B5 (pin 6)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 0) ; //output A0 (pin 8)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 2, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 0) ; //output A3 (pin 11)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 1) ;


    //read output 
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 2) ; //pin 3
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 5) ; //pin 6
    actual_output[2] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 0) ; //pin 8
    actual_output[3] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 3) ; //pin 11


    //testing...
    for (int gate_num = 0; gate_num < 4; gate_num+=1) {
        test_progress.current_gate_num = gate_num;
        snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Test 2: Checking gate %d...", gate_num + 1);
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
        if(actual_output[gate_num] != 0) {
            char testFail[50];
            snprintf(testFail, sizeof(testFail), "010 fault gate %d\n", gate_num + 1);
            strncat(failed_tests, testFail, sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: 010 fault", gate_num + 1);
            gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
            correct = 0;
            test.overall_pass = 0;
            switch(gate_num){
                case 0: 
                    test.pins[2].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 1:
                    test.pins[5].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 2:
                    test.pins[7].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 3:
                    test.pins[10].failed = true;
                    break;
            }
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        }
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
    }


    // Test 3
    test_progress.current_test_num = 3;

    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "test 3: Input 10...", 50);
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(1000);

    // Set input --> 10
    // Expected output --> 0
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 0, 1) ; //output B2 (pin 3)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 1, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 3, 1) ; //output B5 (pin 6)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 1) ; //output A0 (pin 8)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 2, 0) ;

    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 5) ; //pin 6

    actual_output[3] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 3) ; //pin 11

            char testFail[50];
            snprintf(testFail, sizeof(testFail), "100 fault gate %d\n", gate_num + 1);

                case 0:

                    test.pins[5].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 2:
                    test.pins[7].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 3:
                    test.pins[10].failed = true;
                    break;
            }
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        }
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
    }


    // Test 4
    test_progress.current_test_num = 4;
    clear_gate_results();
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "test 4: Input 11...", 50);
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(1000);

    // Set input --> 11
    // Expected output --> 1
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 0, 1) ; //output B2 (pin 3)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 1, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 3, 1) ; //output B5 (pin 6)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 1) ; //output A0 (pin 8)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 2, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 1) ; //output A3 (pin 11)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 1) ;


    //read output 
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 2) ; //pin 3
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 5) ; //pin 6
    actual_output[2] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 0) ; //pin 8
    actual_output[3] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 3) ; //pin 11


    //testing...
    for (int gate_num = 0; gate_num < 4; gate_num+=1) {
        test_progress.current_gate_num = gate_num;
        snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Test 4: Checking gate %d...", gate_num + 1);
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
        if(actual_output[gate_num] != 1) {
            char testFail[50];
            snprintf(testFail, sizeof(testFail), "111 fault gate %d\n", gate_num + 1);
            strncat(failed_tests, testFail, sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: 111 fault", gate_num + 1);
            gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
            correct = 0;
            test.overall_pass = 0;
            switch(gate_num){
                case 0: 
                    test.pins[2].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 1:
                    test.pins[5].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 2:
                    test.pins[7].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 3:
                    test.pins[10].failed = true;
                    break;
            }
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        } 
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
    }




    //return values
    if(correct == 1){
        gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 1);
        test.overall_pass = 1;
    }

    test_progress.test_in_progress = false;
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "Test complete!", 50);

    return test;
}

ICTestDisplay test_NAND(ICTestDisplay  test) {
    PEinit() ;
    bool correct = 1;
    failed_tests[0] = '\0';

    test_progress.test_in_progress = true;
    test_progress.total_tests = 4;
    test_progress.total_gates = 4;
    clear_gate_results();

    //reset status LEDs
    gpio_put(LED_RED, 0);
    gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 0);

    //set ports for inverter
    // 1 --> output
    // 0 --> input
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTA, 0xf6) ; // 1111 0110 --> 0xf6 15 6
    
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTB, 0xdb) ; // 1101 1011 --> 0xdb 13 11

    //results 
    bool actual_output[4];

    // Test 1 
    test_progress.current_test_num = 1;
    clear_gate_results();
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "Test 1: Input 00...", 50);
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(1000);

    // Set input --> 00
    // Expected output --> 1
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 0, 0) ; //output B2 (pin 3)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 1, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 3, 0) ; //output B5 (pin 6)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 0) ; //output A0 (pin 8)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 2, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 0) ; //output A3 (pin 11)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 0) ;


    //read output 
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 2) ; //pin 3
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 5) ; //pin 6
    actual_output[2] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 0) ; //pin 8
    actual_output[3] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 3) ; //pin 11


    //testing...
    for (int gate_num = 0; gate_num < 4; gate_num+=1) {
        test_progress.current_gate_num = gate_num;
        snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Test 1: Checking gate %d...", gate_num + 1);
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);

        if(actual_output[gate_num] != 1) {
            char testFail[50];
            snprintf(testFail, sizeof(testFail), "001 fault gate %d\n", gate_num + 1);
            strncat(failed_tests, testFail, sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: 001 fault", gate_num + 1);
            gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
            correct = 0;
            test.overall_pass = 0;
            switch(gate_num){
                case 0: 
                    test.pins[2].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 1:
                    test.pins[5].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 2:
                    test.pins[7].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 3:
                    test.pins[10].failed = true;
                    break;
            }
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        }
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
    }

    clear_gate_results();

    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(1000);

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 0) ; //output A0 (pin 8)

                    break;
                case 2:
                    test.pins[7].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 3:
                    test.pins[10].failed = true;

            }
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        }

        sleep_ms(500);
    }


    // Test 4

    clear_gate_results();
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "test 4: Input 11...", 50);
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(1000);
    // Set input --> 11
    // Expected output --> 0
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 0, 1) ; //output B2 (pin 3)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 1, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 3, 1) ; //output B5 (pin 6)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 1) ; //output A0 (pin 8)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 2, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 1) ; //output A3 (pin 11)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 1) ;


    //read output 
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 2) ; //pin 3
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 5) ; //pin 6
    actual_output[2] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 0) ; //pin 8
    actual_output[3] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 3) ; //pin 11


    //testing...
    for (int gate_num = 0; gate_num < 4; gate_num+=1) {
        test_progress.current_gate_num = gate_num;
        snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Test 4: Checking gate %d...", gate_num + 1);
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
        if(actual_output[gate_num] != 0) {
            char testFail[50];
            snprintf(testFail, sizeof(testFail), "110 fault gate %d\n", gate_num + 1);
            strncat(failed_tests, testFail, sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);

            gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);

                    break;
                case 2:
                    test.pins[7].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 3:
                    test.pins[10].failed = true;
                    break;
            }
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        }
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
    }
        //return values
    if(correct == 1){
        gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 1);
        test.overall_pass = 1;
    }
    test_progress.test_in_progress = false;
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "Test complete!", 50);
    return test;
    	
}

ICTestDisplay test_OR(ICTestDisplay  test) {
    PEinit() ;
    bool correct = 1;
    failed_tests[0] = '\0';

    test_progress.test_in_progress = true;
    test_progress.total_tests = 4;
    test_progress.total_gates = 4;
    clear_gate_results();

    //reset status LEDs
    gpio_put(LED_RED, 0);
    gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 0);

    //set ports for inverter
    // 1 --> output
    // 0 --> input
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTA, 0xf6) ; // 1111 0110 --> 0xf6 15 6
    
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTB, 0xdb) ; // 1101 1011 --> 0xdb 13 11

    //results 
    bool actual_output[4];

    // Test 1 
    test_progress.current_test_num = 1;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 0) ; //output A0 (pin 8)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 2, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 0) ; //output A3 (pin 11)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 0) ;

            gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
            correct = 0;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 0, 1) ; //output A2 (pin 10)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 1) ; //output A5 (pin 13)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 1, 1) ; //output B0 (pin 1)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 2, 0) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 1) ; //output B3 (pin 4)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 5, 0) ;


    //read output 
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 0) ; //pin 1
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 3) ; //pin 4
    actual_output[2] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 2) ; //pin 10
    actual_output[3] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 5) ; //pin 13


    //testing...
    for (int gate_num = 0; gate_num < 4; gate_num+=1) {
        test_progress.current_gate_num = gate_num;
        snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Test 3: Checking gate %d...", gate_num + 1);
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);

        if(actual_output[gate_num] != 0) {
            char testFail[50];
            snprintf(testFail, sizeof(testFail), "100 fault gate %d\n", gate_num + 1);
            strncat(failed_tests, testFail, sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: 100 fault", gate_num + 1);

            gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
            correct = 0;
            test.overall_pass = 0;
            switch(gate_num){
                case 0: 
                    test.pins[0].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 1:
                    test.pins[3].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 2:
                    test.pins[9].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 3:
                    test.pins[12].failed = true;
                    break;
            }
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        }
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
    }


    // Test 4
    test_progress.current_test_num = 4;
    clear_gate_results();
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "test 4: Input 11...", 50);
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(1000);
    // Set input --> 11
    // Expected output --> 0
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 0, 1) ; //output A2 (pin 10)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 1, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 1) ; //output A5 (pin 13)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 1, 1) ; //output B0 (pin 1)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 2, 1) ;

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 4, 1) ; //output B3 (pin 4)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 5, 1) ;


    //read output 
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 0) ; //pin 1
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 3) ; //pin 4
    actual_output[2] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 2) ; //pin 10
    actual_output[3] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 5) ; //pin 13


    //testing...
    for (int gate_num = 0; gate_num < 4; gate_num+=1) {
        test_progress.current_gate_num = gate_num;
        snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Test 4: Checking gate %d...", gate_num + 1);
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);

        if(actual_output[gate_num] != 0) {
            //################## BEGIN AI-GENERATED CODE ##################
            char testFail[50];
            snprintf(testFail, sizeof(testFail), "001 fault gate %d\n", gate_num + 1);
            strncat(failed_tests, testFail, sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: 001 fault", gate_num + 1);

            //################### END AI-GENERATED CODE ###################
            gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
            correct = 0;
            test.overall_pass = 0;
            switch(gate_num){
                case 0: 
                    test.pins[0].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 1:
                    test.pins[3].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 2:
                    test.pins[9].failed = true;
                    break;
                case 3:
                    test.pins[12].failed = true;
                    break;
            }
        } else {
            snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[gate_num], 50, "Gate %d: PASSED", gate_num + 1);
        }
        update_vga_display();
        sleep_ms(500);
    }

    //return values
    if(correct == 1){
        gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 1);
        test.overall_pass = 1;
    }
    return test;
    	
}


ICTestDisplay test_DFF(ICTestDisplay  test) {
    PEinit() ;
    bool correct = 1;
    failed_tests[0] = '\0';


    test_progress.test_in_progress = true;
    test_progress.total_tests = 2;
    test_progress.total_gates = 2;
    clear_gate_results();


    //reset status LEDs
    gpio_put(LED_RED, 0);
    gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 0);

    // Set Ports
    // 1 --> output
    // 0 --> input
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTA, 0xfc) ; // 1111 1100 --> 0xfc 
    
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTB, 0xcf) ; // 1100 1111 --> 0xcf

    //results 
    bool actual_output[4];

    // ***********************
    // Clock Cycle 1 (D = 1)
    // ***********************
    test_progress.current_test_num = 1;
    clear_gate_results();
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "Cycle 1: D=1...", 50);
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(1000);

    //PORT A --------------------------------------------
    test_progress.current_gate_num = 0;
    snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Cycle 1: Testing DFF A...");
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(500);
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 2, 1) ; //PR (A2, pin 10)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 0) ; //CLK (A3, pin 11)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 1) ; //D (A4, pin 12)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 1) ; //CLR (A5, pin 13)
   
    sleep_us(5);

    // rising edge 
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 1); //CLK
    sleep_us(5);

    // read Q and /Q
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 0); // ~Q
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 1); // Q

    // Expected: ~Q = 0
    if (actual_output[0] != 0 ) {
        strncat(failed_tests, "DFF A ~Q fault cycle 1\n", sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[0], 50, "DFF A ~Q fault (D = 1)");
        gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
        correct = 0;
        test.overall_pass = 0;

        test.pins[7].failed = true; 
    }
    //Expected: Q = 1
   else if (actual_output[1] != 1 ) {
        strncat(failed_tests, "DFF A Q fault cycle 1\n", sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[0], 50, "DFF A ~Q fault (D = 1)");
        gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
        correct = 0;
        test.overall_pass = 0;

        test.pins[8].failed = true; 
    } else {
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[0], 50, "EFF A: PASSED");
    }
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(500);

    //PORT B --------------------------------------------
    test_progress.current_gate_num = 0;
    snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Cycle 1: Testing DFF B...");
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(500);

    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 3, 1) ; //PR (B2, pin 4)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 2, 0) ; //CLK (B3, pin 3)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 1, 1) ; //D (B4, pin 2)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 0, 1) ; //CLR (B5, pin 1)
   
    sleep_us(5);

    // rising edge 
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 2, 1); //CLK
    sleep_us(5);

    // read Q and /Q
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 5); // ~Q
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 4); // Q

    // Expected: ~Q = 0
    if (actual_output[0] != 0 ) {
        strncat(failed_tests, "DFF B ~Q fault cycle 1\n", sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[0], 50, "DFF B ~Q fault (D = 1)");
        gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
        correct = 0;
        test.overall_pass = 0;

        test.pins[5].failed = true; 
    }
    //Expected: Q = 1
    else if (actual_output[1] != 1 ) {
        strncat(failed_tests, "DFF B Q fault cycle 1\n", sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[0], 50, "DFF B ~Q fault (D = 1)");
        gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
        correct = 0;
        test.overall_pass = 0;

        test.pins[4].failed = true; 
    } else {
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[1], 50, "DFF B: PASSED");
    }
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(500);

    // ***********************
    // Clock Cycle 2 (D = 0)
    // ***********************
    test_progress.current_test_num = 2;
    clear_gate_results();
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "Cycle 2: D=0...", 50);
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(1000);
    //PORT A ---------------------------------------------
    test_progress.current_gate_num = 0;
    snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Cycle 2: Testing DFF A...");
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(500);
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 2, 1) ; //PR (A2, pin 10)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 0) ; //CLK (A3, pin 11)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 0) ; //D (A4, pin 12)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 1) ; //CLR (A5, pin 13)
   
    sleep_us(5);

    // rising edge 
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 1); //CLK
    sleep_us(5);

    // read Q and /Q
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 0); // ~Q
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTA, 1); // Q

    // Expected: ~Q = 1
    if (actual_output[0] != 1 ) {
        strncat(failed_tests, "DFF A ~Q fault cycle 2\n", sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[0], 50, "DFF A ~Q fault (D = 0)");
        gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
        correct = 0;
        test.overall_pass = 0;

        test.pins[7].failed = true; 
    } 
    //Expected: Q = 0
    else if (actual_output[1] != 0 ) {
        strncat(failed_tests, "DFF A Q fault cycle 2\n", sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[0], 50, "DFF A ~Q fault (D = 0)");
        gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
        correct = 0;
        test.overall_pass = 0;

        test.pins[8].failed = true; 
    } else {
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[1], 50, "DFF A: PASSED");
    }
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(500);

    //PORT B ---------------------------------------------
    test_progress.current_gate_num = 1;
    snprintf(test_progress.current_status, 50, "Cycle 2: Testing DFF B...");
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(500);
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 3, 1) ; //PR (B2, pin 4)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 2, 0) ; //CLK (B3, pin 3)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 1, 0) ; //D (B4, pin 2)
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 0, 1) ; //CLR (B5, pin 1)
   
    sleep_us(5);

    // rising edge 
    PEwriteBit(PORTB, 2, 1); //CLK
    sleep_us(5);

    // read Q and /Q
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 5); // ~Q
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 4); // Q

    // Expected: ~Q = 1
    if (actual_output[0] != 1 ) {
        strncat(failed_tests, "DFF B ~Q fault cycle 2\n", sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[0], 50, "DFF B ~Q fault (D = 0)");
        gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
        correct = 0;
        test.overall_pass = 0;

        test.pins[5].failed = true; 
    }
    //Expected: Q = 0
    else if (actual_output[1] != 0 ) {
        strncat(failed_tests, "DFF B Q fault cycle 2\n", sizeof(failed_tests) - strlen(failed_tests) - 1);
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[0], 50, "DFF B Q fault (D = 0)");
        gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
        correct = 0;
        test.overall_pass = 0;

        test.pins[4].failed = true; 
    } else {
        snprintf(test_progress.gate_results[1], 50, "DFF B: PASSED");
    }
    update_vga_display();
    sleep_ms(500);

    // ****************
    // DONE
    // ****************
    if (correct == 1) {
        gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 1);
        test.overall_pass = 1;
    }
    test_progress.test_in_progress = false;
    strncpy(test_progress.current_status, "Test complete!", 50);
    return test;
}
        

        

          ate_variables.c
        

        
          //Varibles needed in ate.c and atpg.c

#define LED_GREEN 8
#define LED_RED 9


typedef struct {
    int pin_num;
    bool failed;
    bool is_power;
    bool is_ground;
} PinStatus;

typedef struct {
    char *ic_name;
    int overall_pass;
    PinStatus pins[14];       
} ICTestDisplay;

// Track test progress
typedef struct {
    int current_test_num; // NOT (Test 1 - 2), AND (Test 1-4), NAND (Test 1-4), OR (Test 1-4), NOR (Test 1-4), DFF (Test 1-2, clock cycle 1 & 2)
    int total_tests; // NOT (2 tests), DFF (2 tests), others (4 tests)
    int current_gate_num; // which gate is being tested: NOT (gate 1 - 6), DFF (gate 1 - 2), others (gate 1 - 4)
    int total_gates; // total gates: NOT (6 gates), DFF (2 gates), others (4 gates)
    char current_status[50]; // display which test is being runned and on which gate (for example: Running test 2 on gate 1...)
    char gate_results[6][50]; // maximum of 6 gates for NOT, each string length not sure if enough (display gate test result for test being runned)
    bool test_in_progress; // true --> display current_status on vga screen, false --> display final results (gate_reults) or test not running
} TestProgress;

char failed_tests[500] ;
TestProgress test_progress;

User: "how to bitmap a 7404 ic image to a vga display?"

ChatGPT: Here’s the whole process of how to take a bitmap image of a 7404 IC (or any small image) and display it on a VGA screen using a microcontroller such as the RP2040, MSP430, PIC, AVR, etc.

✅ 1. Understand the VGA Format You’re Outputting

Most student VGA projects use:

Resolution: 640×480 or 320×240

Color: 8-bit or 16-bit RGB

Frame buffer: Either full framebuffer in RAM or tile-based / line-based rendering

Before anything else, ask yourself:

Do you have a full framebuffer in RAM?

RP2040 with PIO often has a framebuffer if resolution is low (e.g., 320×240).

Many MCUs cannot hold a framebuffer (640×480×2 bytes ≈ 614 kB).

If you can’t store a full framebuffer, you must stream the bitmap line-by-line.

✅ 2. Convert Your IC Image into a Bitmap

You need the image in a simple format the microcontroller can store.

A. Choose your target bitmap format

Most common format:

RGB565 (16-bit) 


Or if you only have 1 bit per pixel:

1-bit monochrome (black/white)

B. Resize the 7404 IC image

Use GIMP, Paint.NET, or online tools:

Resize to something like 64×32 or 128×64

Reduce color depth (e.g., grayscale or monochrome)

C. Export as raw pixel array

You can use online tools:
"image2cpp" (Arduino tool) → produces C array.

This gives you something like:

const uint16_t ic7404_bitmap[64*32] = {
    0xFFFF, 0xFFFF, 0x0000, …
};


or for 1-bit monochrome:

const uint8_t ic7404_bitmap[] = {
    0xFF, 0xE0, 0x7C, 0x3F, ...
};

✅ 3. Store the Bitmap in Flash

Put it in flash memory:

const uint16_t ic7404_bitmap[2048] __attribute__((aligned(4))) = { … };

✅ 4. Draw Bitmap to VGA Framebuffer

If you have a framebuffer (e.g., uint16_t framebuf[320][240]):

else
    pixel = BLACK;

✅ Updated Function
void draw_ic_chip(int x, int y) {
    int ic_width  = 80;
    int ic_height = 120;

    // Draw background and border
    fillRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, BLACK);
    drawRect(x, y, ic_width, ic_height, WHITE);

    // Draw bitmap inside the chip area
    for (int row = 0; row < ic_height; row++) {
        for (int col = 0; col < ic_width; col++) {
            uint16_t pixel = ic7404_bitmap[row * ic_width + col];

            // Skip transparent pixels if you want transparency:
            // if (pixel == 0x0000) continue;

            drawPixel(x + col, y + row, pixel);
        }
    }
}

✔ Notes / Tips
1. Bitmap indexing

Your bitmap is linear, so pixel (col, row) is at:

row * ic_width + col

2. If your VGA library expects RGB332 or RGB888

If your VGA code uses a different format, convert:

uint8_t r = (pixel >> 11) & 0x1F;
uint8_t g = (pixel >> 5)  & 0x3F;
uint8_t b = pixel & 0x1F;


I can help adjust the converter if needed.

3. If you want transparency

Just skip drawing black pixels:

if (pixel == 0x0000) continue;

✅ Completed version
ICTestDisplay test_DFF(ICTestDisplay test) {
    PEinit();
    bool correct = 1;

    // reset LEDs
    gpio_put(LED_RED, 0);
    gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 0);

    // Set port directions for DFF
    // 1 = output, 0 = input
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTA, 0xf6); // PR, CLK, D, CLR → outputs
    PEgpioSetDir(PORTB, 0xdb); // Q, Q̅ inputs on B1 and B2

    bool actual_output[2]; // [0] = Q, [1] = /Q

    //
    // ******* CLOCK CYCLE 1 ********
    //

    // Inputs for first cycle
    // NOTE: adjust if your pin mapping differs!
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 2, 1); // PR = 1
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 0); // CLK = 0 (initial)
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 1); // D = 1
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 5, 1); // CLR = 1

    sleep_us(5);

    // rising edge → latch D
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 1);
    sleep_us(5);

    // read Q and /Q
    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 1); // Q
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 2); // /Q

    // Expected: Q = 1, /Q = 0
    if (actual_output[0] != 1 || actual_output[1] != 0) {
        printf("Fault: DFF failed Clock Cycle 1\n");
        gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
        correct = 0;
        test.overall_pass = 0;

        test.pins[0].failed = true; // adjust which pins represent Q/Q̅
    }

    //
    // ******* CLOCK CYCLE 2: test D=0 ********
    //

    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 0); // CLK low
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 4, 0); // change D to 0
    sleep_us(5);

    // rising edge again
    PEwriteBit(PORTA, 3, 1);
    sleep_us(5);

    actual_output[0] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 1); // Q
    actual_output[1] = PEreadBit(PORTB, 2); // /Q

    if (actual_output[0] != 0 || actual_output[1] != 1) {
        printf("Fault: DFF failed Clock Cycle 2\n");
        gpio_put(LED_RED, 1);
        correct = 0;
        test.overall_pass = 0;

        test.pins[0].failed = true;
    }

    //
    // ******* FINAL RETURN ********
    //

    if (correct == 1) {
        gpio_put(LED_GREEN, 1);
        test.overall_pass = 1;
    }

    return test;
}
